<div class="bar">
  <h1 class="brand">Standing Waves</h1>
  <p class="tagline">Why the microwave leaves melted <em>spots</em> instead of melting everything evenly.</p>

  <p>
    A microwave cavity is a closed metal box. The magnetron emits a wave that travels
    across the cavity, reflects off the far (metal) wall, and travels back &mdash; inverted,
    since a wave flips phase when it reflects off a fixed boundary. With the incident and
    reflected waves now travelling in <em>opposite</em> directions at the same frequency,
    they add together to form a <strong>standing wave</strong>: a pattern that no longer
    travels anywhere, but instead oscillates in place.
  </p>

  <a href="#standing-wave-diagram" style="display: block; margin: 1.2rem 0; cursor: zoom-in;">
    <img src="/images/standing-wave-diagram.svg"
         alt="Animated diagram: an incident wave and its inverted reflection travelling in opposite directions sum to a standing wave with double the amplitude at the antinodes and fixed nodes in between"
         style="width: 100%; display: block;">
  </a>

  <p>
    At certain fixed points &mdash; the <strong>nodes</strong> &mdash; the incident and reflected
    waves always cancel exactly, so the field there is always zero. Exactly halfway between
    each pair of nodes sits an <strong>antinode</strong>, where the two waves always reinforce
    each other. There, the combined field swings between <strong>+2A and &minus;2A</strong>:
    double the amplitude of either wave alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Nodes and antinodes are spaced <strong>&lambda;/2</strong> apart, and it's the antinodes
    that matter for the chocolate: field <em>intensity</em> depends on amplitude squared, so
    the antinodes are where the microwave's energy is concentrated into hot spots &mdash;
    exactly where the chocolate melts first. Measure the spacing between melted spots, double
    it to get &lambda;, and the <a href="/calculator">calculator</a> does the rest.
  </p>
</div>

